We can represent the complex number $z$ as $a+bi$, where $a$ and $b$ are real numbers. The conjugate of $z$ is then $\bar{z}=a-bi$.
Plugging these expressions for $z$ and $\bar{z}$ into the given equation $2z-3\bar{z}=-2-30i$, we have
\begin{align*}
2(a+bi)-3(a-bi)&=-2-30i\\
\Rightarrow\qquad (2a+2bi)-3(a-bi)&=-2-30i\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 2a+2bi-3a+3bi&=-2-30i\\
\Rightarrow\qquad (2a-3a)+(2b+3b)i&=-2-30i\\
\Rightarrow\qquad -a+5bi&=-2-30i
\end{align*}
We have two parts, the real and imaginary parts of the equation. Equating these two parts from the equation above and the right-hand side of the equation $-a+5bi=-2-30i$, we get the system of equations
\begin{align*}
-a&=-2\tag{1}\\
5b&=-30.\tag{2}
\end{align*}
Solving each equation for its variable:
\begin{align*}
-a&=-2 \\
\Rightarrow\qquad a&=2 \\
\end{align*}and 
\begin{align*}
5b&=-30 \\
\Rightarrow\qquad b&=-6.
\end{align*} 
So $a=2$ and $b=-6$, then we can write the complex number $z$ as
$$z=a+bi=2+(-6)i=\boxed{2-6i}.$$
Therefore, the complex number $z$ satisfying the equation $2z-3\bar{z}=-2-30i$ is $2-6i$.

